---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout 
  title="About" 
  description="Learn about RAPS and its creator, Dmytro Yemelianov - Autodesk Expert Elite and APS developer."
>
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <!-- Header -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-black text-white mb-6">
          About <span class="text-rapeseed-400">RAPS</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-slate-400">
          Bringing modern DevOps practices to Autodesk Platform Services.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <!-- The Story -->
      <div class="prose prose-invert prose-slate max-w-none mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-display font-bold text-white mb-4">The Story</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          After 15 years of working with Autodesk platforms, one pattern became painfully clear: 
          the AEC industry has embraced sophisticated design technology but still operates these 
          tools with manual, error-prone processes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Software development solved this problem decades ago with CI/CD pipelines. Every code 
          change triggers automated builds, tests, and deployments. Yet in AEC, we're still 
          clicking through web interfaces to upload models and check translation status.
        </p>
        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
          RAPS was built to bridge this gap. It's a command-line interface that makes Autodesk 
          Platform Services accessible to automation pipelines ‚Äî the same way tools like 
          <code>git</code>, <code>docker</code>, and <code>kubectl</code> transformed software 
          deployment.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Why Rust -->
      <div class="mb-16 p-8 bg-gradient-to-br from-rust-500/10 to-slate-900/50 border border-slate-800 rounded-xl">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-display font-bold text-white mb-4">Why <span class="text-rust-500">Rust</span>?</h2>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Performance</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
              Single binary, no runtime dependencies. Starts instantly, handles large file 
              uploads efficiently, and uses minimal memory.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Reliability</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
              Rust's type system catches entire categories of bugs at compile time. 
              No null pointer exceptions, no data races.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Portability</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
              Compiles to native binaries for Windows, macOS (Intel + Apple Silicon), 
              and Linux. No Python, Node, or Java required.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Modern CLI Experience</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
              Built with clap for excellent argument parsing, colored output, 
              shell completions, and helpful error messages.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <!-- About the Author -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-display font-bold text-white mb-8">About the Author</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-8 items-start">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <div class="w-32 h-32 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-accent-500 rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center">
              <span class="text-white font-bold text-4xl">DY</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
